# Six tongues, one lattice — language grammars from the cursor

> The dream of [`bmf-architecture.form`](bmf-architecture.form), carried to the
> languages: BML, Python, Go, Rust, C#, and Java each expressed as a small bag of
> **(pattern ⇒ template)** rules over the cursor — no parse stack, no per-language
> emit code — all generating the **same universal Form nodes** directly. Proven by
> [`form/form-stdlib/tests/bmf-langs-band.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/tests/bmf-langs-band.fk)
> → `300`, `1 ok, 0 divergent` across Go/Rust/TS.

## The one move

Everything left of `=>` is the language's surface — its keywords and punctuation.
Everything right of `=>` is the **universal** shape it emits. The surfaces diverge;
the coordinates converge. A `def`, a `func`, an `fn`, a `void` are four words for
one thing — and the lattice interns them to one NodeID, because the template names
the *meaning* (`~Function`), not the *spelling*.

```
input surface ──▶ Cursor ──▶ Match(grammar) ──▶ ~Universal[…] ──▶ one NodeID
```

The kernel never learns a language. A new language is a new bag of rules; the emit
vocabulary (`~Function`, `~Cond`, `~Binary`, `~Call`, `~Block`, `~Loop`) is shared
by all of them. That sharing is what makes cross-language equivalence *free* — not
declared, not mapped, just the consequence of two grammars emitting the same shape.

## The grammars (a representative slice)

The `::=` / `{ }` / `[ ]` / `< >` / `$tag:` / `\\` are the thesis BMF notation
(see [`bmf-architecture.form`](bmf-architecture.form)); `=> ~Shape[…]` is the
universal emit.

```bmf
grammar python over chars {
  func ::= "def" $name:ID "(" $param:ID \\ "," ")" ":" $body:block       => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" $cond:expr ":" $then:block [ "else" ":" $else:block ]    => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                           => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                     => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
}

grammar go over chars {
  func ::= "func" $name:ID "(" $param:ID \\ "," ")" type? "{" $body:block "}"  => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" $cond:expr "{" $then:block "}" [ "else" "{" $else:block "}" ]  => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                                 => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                           => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
}

grammar rust over chars {
  func ::= "fn" $name:ID "(" $param:ID \\ "," ")" [ "->" type ] "{" $body:block "}" => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" $cond:expr "{" $then:block "}" [ "else" "{" $else:block "}" ]       => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                                      => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                                => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
}

grammar csharp over chars {
  func ::= modifier* type $name:ID "(" $param:param \\ "," ")" "{" $body:block "}" => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" "(" $cond:expr ")" $then:block [ "else" $else:block ]              => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                                     => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                               => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
}

grammar java over chars {
  func ::= modifier* type $name:ID "(" $param:param \\ "," ")" "{" $body:block "}" => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" "(" $cond:expr ")" $then:block [ "else" $else:block ]              => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                                     => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                               => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
}

grammar bml over chars {
  func ::= section_props? type $name:ID "(" $param:param \\ "," ")" "{" $body:block "}" => ~Function[ #name, param*, body ] ;
  if   ::= "if" "(" $cond:expr ")" $then:block [ "else" $else:block ]                   => ~Cond(IF)[ cond, then, else? ] ;
  call ::= $callee:ID "(" $arg:expr \\ "," ")"                                          => ~Call[ callee, arg* ] ;
  add  ::= mul { ( "+" | "-" ) mul }                                                    => fold.left ~Binary(op) ;
  choice ::= "choice" $branch:block \\ ","                                             => ~Choice[ branch* ] ;
}
```

Read the right-hand columns top to bottom: they are **identical**. The only thing
that changed down the page is the surface. BML carries one extra rule (`choice`,
its angelic-nondeterminism construct) because BML is the superset — when a language
has a feature the others lack, it lands in BML; it never changes the engine.

## Convergence — the same construct, the same coordinate

| Construct | Python | Go | Rust | C# / Java | BML | → emits |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| function | `def add(x):` | `func add(x){}` | `fn add(x){}` | `void add(x){}` | `void add(x){}` | **`~Function`** |
| if | `if c:` | `if c {}` | `if c {}` | `if (c) {}` | `if (c) {}` | **`~Cond(IF)`** |
| call | `add(x)` | `add(x)` | `add(x)` | `add(x)` | `add(x)` | **`~Call`** |
| add | `a + b` | `a + b` | `a + b` | `a + b` | `a + b` | **`~Binary(add)`** |

What the proof asserts: parse `add`'s function declaration in all six surfaces, and
every one interns to the *same* `~Function[add, x]` NodeID; parse the `if` in all
six, and every one interns to the same `~Cond(IF)[ready]` NodeID; and the two
shapes stay distinct from each other. That is `300` in the band — six tongues, two
coordinates, zero divergence across three kernels.

## What carries it

- **The cursor reads any surface** — file, string, socket, cell, channel — and is
  whitespace-aware, so the grammars stay clean (no `ws` litter between tokens).
- **Patterns are data** (`lit` / `cls` / `run` / `seq` / `alt` / `opt` / `cap` in
  [`bmf-core.fk`](../../form/form-stdlib/bmf-core.fk)); a language is rule-data, not code.
- **Templates emit universal shapes** via `(bp "fndef")`, `(bp "if-then")`, … so
  content-addressing collapses equivalent constructs to one NodeID with no sameAs
  table and no normalize pass.

## What is proven vs. the staged path

Proven now (in the band, cross-kernel): the **convergence law** — six languages'
function and `if` rules, run from the cursor, land on one universal coordinate each.

The staged path (named, not yet shipped): the full grammars need two core
primitives the band sidesteps — general `{ p }` repetition of sub-patterns and the
`\\` separator-list capturing into a child list (today `bmf-core.fk` repeats only
character classes via `run`, and the band uses fixed arity). Those are the next
breath; with them, `$param:ID \\ ","` captures a real argument list and the
grammars above run verbatim. The law is what mattered to prove first: the surfaces
converge. The rest is filling the bag of rules.
